Overview
This repository contains an R-based analysis of 10X Xenium spatial transcriptomics data from a breast ductal carcinoma in situ (DCIS) tissue sample. The analysis covers quality control, unsupervised clustering, cell type annotation, and spatial proximity analysis, with a focus on the role of myoepithelial cells in the DCIS tumour microenvironment.
Data
Data were retrieved from:

Janesick, A. et al., High resolution mapping of the tumor microenvironment using integrated single-cell, spatial and in situ analysis. Nat Commun. (2023)

The dataset contains:

313 genes (targeted Xenium panel)
167,780 cells (161,789 after QC filtering)

The pipeline along with analysis is available at https://parulkuls26.github.io/Xenium-DCIS-Spatial-Transcriptomics-Analysis/Xenium%20DCIS%20analysis.nb.html

Analysis Pipeline

1. Quality Control — filtering cells based on transcript counts, unique gene counts, and negative probe ratios

2. Normalisation & Feature Selection — log-normalisation and variable gene identification

3. Data Sketching — representative subset of 75,000 cells for efficient clustering

4. Dimensionality Reduction & Clustering — PCA, Louvain clustering (32 clusters), and UMAP visualisation

5. Cell Type Annotation — differential expression analysis and marker-based annotation (15 cell types identified)

6. Spatial Proximity Analysis — k-nearest neighbour distance analysis between myoepithelial cells and all other cell types

Key Findings

161,789 cells retained after QC filtering
32 clusters identified, annotated into 15 cell types
Most abundant cell types: Glandular cells, T cells, Fibroblasts
Myoepithelial cells are significantly closer to Glandular cells (median distance: 13.39 µm) than to any other cell type, confirming their role as a protective monolayer around ductal structures

Requirements

R version
R ≥ 4.4.0
R Packages

Visualisation: ggplot2, ggpubr, ggsci, patchwork

Data manipulation: plyr, dplyr, tidyverse, magrittr, Matrix

Spatial analysis: sf, FNN

Single-cell analysis: Seurat

Utilities: DT

Usage

1. Clone the repository

2. Install all required packages by running the dependency installation chunk at the top of the notebook

3. Update the file paths in the data loading chunks to match your local directory

4. Run the notebook chunk by chunk or knit to HTML

License

This analysis was conducted for educational purposes as part of a spatial transcriptomics practical.
